content: Yes, **PUT /vault creates parent directories automatically**. Looking at the code:

## Auto-creation of Parent Folders

In `src/requestHandler.ts`, the `_vaultPut` method explicitly creates parent directories:

```typescript
async _vaultPut(
  filepath: string,
  req: express.Request,
  res: express.Response,
): Promise<void> {
  if (!filepath || filepath.endsWith("/")) {
    this.returnCannedResponse(res, {
      errorCode: ErrorCode.RequestMethodValidOnlyForFiles,
    });
    return;
  }

  try {
    await this.app.vault.createFolder(path.dirname(filepath));
  } catch {
    // the folder/file already exists, but we don't care
  }

  if (typeof req.body === "string") {
    await this.app.vault.adapter.write(filepath, req.body);
  } else {
    await this.app.vault.adapter.writeBinary(
      filepath,
      toArrayBuffer(req.body),
    );
  }

  this.returnCannedResponse(res, { statusCode: 204 });
  return;
}
```

**Key points:**
- `path.dirname(filepath)` extracts the parent directory path
- `createFolder()` creates the entire directory tree if needed
- Errors are caught and ignored (folder already exists)
- This happens for both text and binary content

## Example Usage

```bash
# Creates folder1/folder2/folder3/ automatically if they don't exist
PUT /vault/folder1/folder2/folder3/myfile.md
```

## Note
The same auto-creation logic exists in `_vaultPost` (line references show identical pattern), so **POST also creates parent directories automatically**.
